{{DISPLAYTITLE:Philosophy and religion in ''Star Wars''}}
[[George Lucas]]' creation of the ''[[Star Wars]]'' saga was influenced by certain elements of mythology, philosophy and religion. In particular, the conflict between "light" and "dark" sides of the [[Force (Star Wars)|Force]] resembles [[Zoroastrianism]], while their close connection recalls the [[yin and yang]] of [[Taoism]]:

{{quote|text=Lucas's dualism may have been modeled on Chinese yin-yang notions in some ways, but it has equal inspiration from the Zoroastrian ethical dualism of good and evil. Both the dark (yin) and the light (yang) are present in the Force (as they are in Tao), but in Star Wars the dark is associated with evil and the light with good; in Taoism no such ethical links are made.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kraemer |first1=Ross |last2=Cassidy |first2=William |last3=Schwartz |first3=Susan L. |date=2009 |title=Religions Of Star Trek |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=FfBJSfmRhm0C&pg=PT53 |publisher=Basic Books |isbn=0786750227 }}</ref>}}

There is therefore an inconsistency in Lucas's ideas between the duality of yin/yang (which should be in balance with each other) and the duality of good/evil (where evil is viewed as wrong).<ref>{{cite book |last=Jamilla |first=Nick |editor1-last=Brode |editor1-first=Douglas |editor2-last=Deyneka |editor2-first=Leah |date=2012 |title=Sex, Politics, and Religion in Star Wars: An Anthology |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=fHgKDWAZ0SIC&pg=PA156 |chapter=Chapter 12: Defining the Jedi Order |pages=156–157 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |isbn=081088514X }}</ref> There is nevertheless a strong ethical element to ''Star Wars'', which has been linked to that of [[Buddhism]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Robinson |first=Walter R. |editor1-last=Decker |editor1-first=Kevin S. |editor2-last=Eberl |editor2-first=Jason T. |editor3-last=Irwin |editor3-first=William |date=2013 |title=Star Wars and Philosophy: More Powerful than You Can Possibly Imagine |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=U7VOAiIvMSUC |chapter=Chapter 3: The Far East of ''Star Wars'' |publisher=Open Court |isbn=0812697014 }}</ref> and [[Stoicism]]:

{{quote|text=To recap, the virtues the Jedi shares with the Stoic sage are patience, timeliness, deep commitment, seriousness (as opposed to frivolity), calmness (as opposed to anger or euphoria), peacefulness (as opposed to aggression), caution (as opposed to recklessness), benevolence (as opposed to hatred), joy (as opposed to sullenness), passivity (as opposed to agitation), and wisdom. Given all these virtues, Yoda certainly resembles what the ancient Stoics described as the sage—the ideal person who has perfected his reason and achieved complete wisdom.<ref>{{cite book |last=Stephens |first=William O. |editor1-last=Decker |editor1-first=Kevin S. |editor2-last=Eberl |editor2-first=Jason T. |editor3-last=Irwin |editor3-first=William |date=2013 |title=Star Wars and Philosophy: More Powerful than You Can Possibly Imagine |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=U7VOAiIvMSUC |chapter=Chapter 2: "Stoicism in the stars: Yoda, the Emperor, and the Force |publisher=Open Court |isbn=0812697014 }}</ref>}}

The concept of [[evil]] in ''Star Wars'' also resembles that of [[Manichaeism]].<ref name="MarkRowlands"/> However, since [[Christianity]] views evil as the absence of good, rather than as something real in itself, the concept of evil in ''Star Wars'' conflicts with that of Christianity.<ref name="MarkRowlands">{{cite book |last=Rowlands |first=Mark |date=2012 |title=The Philosopher At The End Of The Universe: Philosophy Explained Through Science Fiction Films |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=cmwsL2AdE_cC&pg=PT122 |page=214 |publisher=Random House |isbn=1448116678}}</ref>

The physical aspects of the [[Force (Star Wars)|Force]] in ''Star Wars'' have been compared to [[Qi]] in Chinese and Japanese thought.<ref>{{cite book |last=Jamilla |first=Nick |date=2008 |title=Sword Fighting in the Star Wars Universe: Historical Origins, Style and Philosophy |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=g23D4YMmdb0C&pg=PA45 |page=45 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=0786451793}}</ref> In [[Star Wars (film)|the first film]] it is described this way:

{{quote|text=Well, the Force is what gives a Jedi his power. It's an energy field created by all living things. It surrounds us and penetrates us. It binds the galaxy together.<ref name="Episode IV">[[Obi-Wan Kenobi]] ([[Alec Guinness]]) in ''Star Wars Episode IV: A New Hope''</ref>}}

Connections of the Force to [[Prana]] in Hindu thought have also been suggested, but this has been criticised as a misinterpretation which confuses the [[Paramatman]] with the individual soul.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rosen |first1=Steven J. |authorlink1=Steven J. Rosen |last2=Young | first2=Jonathan |title=The Jedi in the Lotus: Star Wars and the Hindu Tradition |year=2010 |publisher=Arktos |isbn=978-1-907166-11-2 |pages=109–110 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=ud9x63jUFu8C&pg=PA109 }}</ref>


